benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/allCustomFields - Retrieve account customFields

covered: Valid Request: Multiple TC scenarios cover successful retrieval with various parameter configurations (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05, TC06, TC07, TC08, TC09, TC10).
Error Handling: Tests for invalid accountId formats (TC12, TC33), non-existent account (TC13), and XSS/invalid parameter inputs (TC18, TC32).
Authentication/Authorization: Tests for missing token (TC14) and invalid token (TC15).
Service Unavailability & Recovery: Tests for API downtime (TC16), transient recovery (TC20), and integration dependency failures (TC23).
Edge and Regression: Coverage for regression scenarios (TC21, TC22, TC39) and edge cases (TC29, TC30, TC31, TC33, TC34, TC35, TC36, TC37, TC38).
Performance/Scalability: Large dataset handling (TC11) and concurrency/basic performance expectations (TC25, TC26).
State / Data Variants: Degraded or partially populated state (TC27, TC28).
gaps: Pagination: No tests explicitly verify pagination handling when the dataset is large or paginated responses are requested across pages.
Caching Behavior: No tests validating caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or client caching implications.
Authorization - 403 path: No explicit test ensuring a authenticated user with insufficient permissions receives 403 Forbidden.
Rate Limiting: No scenarios around rate limits or throttling under load.

Edge - extreme invalid formats: Some edge cases exist (e.g., extremely long IDs, whitespace-only IDs addressed in TC33-35, but broader negative input format coverage could be deeper in other parameter combinations).
recommendations: Add a dedicated pagination test to verify correct page size, page tokens, and total counts for large result sets.
Add tests to validate caching headers like ETag and Cache-Control and their impact on repeated requests.
Add a 403 Forbidden scenario to confirm proper handling when an authenticated user lacks required permissions.
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure graceful handling under high request volume.
Consider additional edge-case coverage for extremely long IDs and more varied invalid objectType/audit inputs to strengthen input validation.
